##Wu soft students say things were thrown away after the commandeering of the dormitory, the vice principal wronged

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

By Tang Qi, _ paper _ News, Wuhan

A city-owned university in Wuhan has become embroiled in a public opinion storm.

At about 11:00 noon on February 7, the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering at Wuhan's Donghu New Technology Development Zone received an urgent notice that the school needed to vacate 1,000 student dormitories, as an isolation point for close contacts of the novel Coronavirus (hereinafter referred to as "NCP") . On the same day, the school will release the "report to students" , informed of the number of the dormitory to be requisitioned, and promised that students' personal belongings will be properly managed.

Colleges and universities around the country are delaying the start of classes to prevent and control the epidemic. Still on holiday, the school has recalled more than 200 staff members to help clear out the dormitories.

Plans Change. The next day, February 8, the school was told to vacate another 1,000 dormitories. Under the pressure of the heavy cleaning work, the school failed to inform the students in time this time.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering. This photo is by Tang Qitu, _ thepaper.cn _

On Feb. 9, students at the school saw photos in the dormitories, where an open space under the building's patio was strewn with objects and others were rummaging through students'lockers and dropping them on the floor. For a while, various videos and photos began to go viral on the Internet, pointing to the school as "brutally emptying the students' dormitories" , sparking netizens' dissatisfaction.

Sun Meihua felt very helpless. As Vice President of the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering, she has not returned home for several days after the assignment, devoting herself to cleaning out her dorm and carrying supplies. "The truth of the matter is not what you saw on the Internet. "

She choked up during an interview with the www.thepaper.cn  on Feb. 10.

Operation Clean Sweep

The Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering is not the only high school that has been commandeered as a quarantine point.

On the evening of February 7, COVID-19 held a regular press conference on the prevention and control of pneumonia in Hubei Province. Hu Yabo, a member of the Standing Committee of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee and Executive Vice Mayor, said the provincial and municipal epidemic prevention headquarters was transforming the Party School of the provincial Party Committee and the University of Wuhan into wards, with an estimated 5,400 additional beds for patients with mild illnesses.

A total of four city-owned universities in Wuhan, including Kong Hon University, Wuhan Business School, Wuhan Ship Vocational and Technical College and Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering, have been notified of the requisition of dormitories. But already the school said that at present the university dormitory only serves as the suspected and the fever patient's isolation spot, whether further serves as the diagnosis mild disease patient's isolation ward also to be decided by the epidemic development.

The Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering was notified at around 11:00 a.m. on Feb. 7 that because of the outbreak, the campus, which was supposed to be bustling, was still closed.

After receiving the notice, the university recalled more than 200 staff members to empty student dormitories and carry materials. On February 7, students were informed of the 1,000 dormitories in 12,13,14,15 and 16 buildings that had been requisitioned.

"Students, please rest assured that the dormitories are all hand-tidied by the teachers, and your personal belongings have been properly kept... the dormitories will be strictly managed by professionals and will be professionally cleaned and disinfected after use to ensure safety and security, " the report said.

The next day, Feb. 8, the school was told to add another 1,000 dormitories as isolation points. This time, there was no further announcement to the students, and the workload of the faculty and staff increased dramatically. In a hurry, some of the seemingly crude cleanup has gone viral, sending the university into a firestorm.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The dormitory has been tidied up, after pictures on the Internet showed it had been filled with rubbish.

On Feb. 9, photos and videos of the university cleaning up its dormitories circulated on the Internet. Photos show the open space beneath the courtyard of the university's dormitory building littered with students'belongings. There were also videos of staff members rummaging through students'lockers and dropping items on the floor. Some students reported that they had not been informed by the school that their personal belongings were not treated with due respect.

All of a sudden, a variety of videos and photos began to go viral on the Internet, pointing the finger at the school, causing netizens dissatisfaction.

At about 1 a.m. on Feb. 10, the official Weibo Account of the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering issued an apology for the incident, which read: "In the process of sorting out individual personnel to catch up with the progress, sorting out not careful, improper handling of the situation. The school apologizes and solemnly promises to compensate all students for the loss of their belongings on the basis of verification."

The grievances of the vice principal and the dedication of the faculty

Sun Meihua, vice president of the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering, was devastated when she learned of public opinion on the afternoon of Feb. 9.

After receiving the task of transforming the isolation point, she has not returned home for several days, devoted to the dormitory empty, material handling work, sometimes at 2 or 3 o'clock at night still in the dormitory building, docking materials.

"We really didn't have detailed communication with students in the early days, and we really didn't have time, " Sun told the paper in an interview on the afternoon of Feb. 10, teachers have been making one-on-one calls to students whose dorms have been requisitioned and explaining the situation. "We want them to trust that their teachers, their students' valuables, their emotional memories, will be there for them. "

The university's student dormitories were nearly full before they were requisitioned.

According to Sun Meihua, they had divided all the students'belongings into three categories before the cleanup: daily necessities, such as bedding and toiletries, were rolled up and put away; and valuables, such as computers, teachers are registered and placed in designated dormitories where they are locked up. The last category is memorabilia, such as awards certificates and postcards, which teachers are required to keep as close to them as possible.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The school has provided student cataloging instructions

According to a number of classified documents provided by the university, thepaper.cn noted that a section of rooms on each floor of the condemned dormitory building will be used as a warehouse for storing other students'belongings whose dormitory has been emptied, and mark the corresponding dormitory number clearly.

"Our school does not have a living area. More than 200 teachers and staff members who came to support us live scattered in the three towns of Wuhan. Some wanted to help, but it was inconvenient because they did not have a car, " Sun said, adding that the majority of female staff at the school, cleaning dormitories, moving materials are also hard work, many teachers are to overcome difficulties and only as soon as possible to empty the dormitory delivery.

On the afternoon of Feb. 10, The Paper made a site visit to the condemned dormitory of the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering, after photos circulated online showed the hall of the garbage strewn dormitory being cleaned up. In dormitory after dormitory, the university prepared washbasins, towels, toilet paper and other daily necessities for the quarantined staff. Some students'slippers, bedding and other items were stuffed into their cabinets, waiting to be sealed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The school provides living materials for those who are about to move into the quarantines

Wang Zhonglin, dean of the mechanical engineering at the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering, who was involved in the cleanup, told The Paper that some items on the Internet that looked like student belongings were thrown on the ground as garbage, but were actually in the process of being cleaned up, indeed, there are many waste paper boxes, empty bottles and other students have not time to throw away the garbage, useful items are absolutely not thrown away.

Wang Zhonglin admitted that because the dormitory is six stories high and there is no elevator, in order to race against time, there is a situation where bags of garbage are thrown directly from the upstairs to ensure that no one is downstairs, resulting in a bad look in the photos, but it was all cleaned up afterwards, and none of the students'valuables were among them.

"We called in all the help we could get, including the 50-year-old professor, who was on his hands and knees cleaning out the garbage under the students' beds and repeatedly mopping the toilets, " Wang said bluntly, the teachers were chagrined by the radical remarks on the Internet.

"The truth of the matter is not exactly what we saw on the Internet. After the epidemic, we still have to face our students. Can Schools not love their students? " Sun Choked up during an interview, blood and tears were visible in both eyes.

Stand by for quarantine

Despite the grievances, the official Weibo Account of the Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering issued an apology at around 1 a.m. on Feb. 10.

The letter said, "In the process of sorting out individual personnel to catch up with the progress, sorting out not careful, improper handling of the situation. The school hereby apologizes and solemnly promises to compensate all students for the loss of their belongings on the basis of verification."

The uproar has gone viral on many people's wechat accounts in Wuhan, with comments such as "students, please don't apply to this school" affecting the mood of Liu Jing (not her real name) , a staff member at the school. These two days, she received many students sent messages, they are out of concern to the school teachers expressed comfort.

On the afternoon of Feb. 10, Ms. Liu saw a group of teachers still posting videos of them rummaging through trash. She told The Paper that the teachers also wanted to see if there were any useful items they had accidentally thrown away, but that they were rummaging through the trash.

There are also school teachers posting on Weibo how they clean out student dormitories -- as if anything that can be put in a closet is never put out, and anything that can be put out is packed in boxes, even some unused disposable chopsticks were not thrown away, even a poster posted on the Cabinet Yiyang Qianxi, the teacher carefully tore down, rolled up and put it in the cabinet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some of the student's belongings were stuffed into a locker, waiting to be sealed.

"When disaster strikes, everyone reacts differently, and sometimes what warms people is those who don't care about their efforts. " Liu Jing lamented that the teachers' efforts have a clear conscience, and they have been fighting for days and nights regardless of safety and security, should be the focus.

Today, the dormitories that have been commandeered are quiet, waiting for the quarantines who will move in. At that time, the dormitories will also be professionally managed.

Why is Wuhan Vocational College of Software and Engineering a target when the dorm is also empty?

"maybe we have cleared out all the waste paper boxes and other rubbish that the children don't want. If we don't take care of this, it's OK, but it's irresponsible for the students, " Wang said as he repeated the offer.

(interns Xia Mengjie, Meng Jinjin, Zhang Haorong and Yan caiqi contributed to this report.)
